    icon: 'tabler:door', 
  },
  {
    title: 'Home Energy Audit',
    description: 'Conduct a home energy audit to identify areas for improvement and create a roadmap for energy-efficient upgrades.',
    limit: 'Up to $150',
    icon: 'tabler:list-tree',  
  },
]}
/>

  <!-- Featured Articles Widget ******************* -->
  
  <FeaturedArticles 
  title="Featured Articles" 
  articleSlugs={[
    'what-is-the-energy-efficient-home-credit',
    'crafting-an-energy-efficient-strategy',
    'biomass-boilers-explained',
    'iot-is-fueling-smart-energy-devices',
    'whats-an-air-source-heat-pump',
    'whats-a-heat-pump-water-heater',
    'comprehensive-guide-to-weatherization',
    'whats-a-ductless-mini-split-heat-pump',
  ]}  
/>

<FAQs
  title="Frequently Asked Questions"
  columns={1}
  items={[
    {
      title: 'What Is the Annual Limit of 25C?',
      description: 'As of January 1, 2023, the annual limit for the 25C credit is $3,200, a significant increase from the previous lifetime limit of $500. This makes it even more beneficial for homeowners to invest in energy-efficient improvements.'
    },
    {
      title: 'Understanding the Energy Efficient Home Improvement Tax Credit (25C)',
      description: 'The Energy Efficient Home Improvement Tax Credit, commonly known as 25C, is a federal incentive promoting energy-efficient upgrades in homes. This credit aims to encourage homeowners to adopt best energy-efficient upgrades, enhancing overall home energy efficiency.'
    },
    {
      title: 'Eligibility Criteria for Energy Efficient Home Improvements',
      description: 'Qualifying for the 25C credit involves specific improvements, primarily focusing on heating, cooling, and water heating systems, which are major contributors to household utility costs. Eligible upgrades include air-source heat pumps, tankless water heaters, biomass boilers, insulation, energy-efficient windows, and more'
    },
    {
      title: 'Are Home Energy Tax Credits Refundable?',
      description: 'The Energy Efficient Home Improvement Tax Credit offers an annual limit of $3,200. However, it is non-refundable and non-rollover; it is applied to reduce your tax liability for the year. It is essential to understand how this credit impacts your tax obligations or potential refunds.'
    },
    {
      title: 'Tax Credit Eligibility for New Windows and Doors',
      description: 'Yes, under the 25C credit, certain energy-efficient windows and exterior doors qualify for a tax credit. Investing in energy credit new windows and doors not only enhances your energy efficiency but also contributes to a $500 energy tax credit.'
    }
  ]}
/>


